				\begin{document}$$n_{E}(0), n_{I}(0)$$\end{document}nE(0),nI(0) by rounding the continuous output of the multivariate normal distribution. We can do this without a large error as these parameters vary smoothly over a large range. For the parameter k we employ an adaptive discrete transition that assigns probabilities to all possible parameter values directly from the frequency of the respective value in the population of accepted particles with additional random jumps (with probability 0.3) to ensure absolute continuity of the prior. The process is repeated until the acceptance threshold is sufficiently low; we especially ensured that the threshold is considerably lower than the difference between the reported cases and the seven-day rolling average of cases.

